@Sachin shajan I had the same problem. Plus I couldn't just run psql. From powershell I was asked if I trusted it, and if so, to give the command ./psql; only that way did it work. When it asked for my password then, it was asking for the postgres password, and not my Windows login username password. I had no problem setting an environmental variable adding the bin location to the path. I didn't have to add -h localhost -W. It went straight to postgres=# prompt, But I did get this warning: WARNING: Console code page (437) differs from Windows code page (1252)
         8-bit characters might not work correctly. See psql reference
         page "Notes for Windows users" for details. I hope this helps someone. You could always write a batch script file. In Notepad, write the command you are giving with all the flags. Name that file psql.bat, but make sure you don't have a psql.bat file already in the bin directory. If you then type psql, it will run the batch file.

